'''North Carolina Highway 138''' ('''NC&nbsp;138''') is a primary [[state highway]] in the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[North Carolina]].  It serves to connect the community of [[Aquadale, North Carolina|Aquadale]] to nearby [[Oakboro, North Carolina|Oakboro]] and [[Albemarle, North Carolina|Albemarle]].

==Route description==
NC&nbsp;138 is a two-lane rural highway that begins immediately after [[North Carolina Highway 742|NC&nbsp;742]] begins, in downtown [[Oakboro, North Carolina|Oakboro]].  Going east, it crosses over Long Creek, an tributary of the [[Rocky River (North Carolina)|Rocky River]], then proceeds northeast to [[Aquadale, North Carolina|Aquadale]].  After crossing a railroad track, in Aquadale, it goes north to end at [[U.S. Route 52 in North Carolina|US&nbsp;52]], just south of [[Albemarle, North Carolina|Albemarle]].

==History==
NC&nbsp;138 was established in 1973 as a new primary routing from [[North Carolina Highway 742|NC&nbsp;742]], in [[Oakboro, North Carolina|Oakboro]], through [[Aquadale, North Carolina|Aquadale]], to [[U.S. Route 52 in North Carolina|US&nbsp;52]]/[[North Carolina Highway 24|NC&nbsp;24]]/[[North Carolina Highway 27|NC&nbsp;27]]/[[North Carolina Highway 73|NC&nbsp;73]], in [[Albemarle, North Carolina|Albemarle]].<ref>{{cite map |publisher= North Carolina Department of Transportation |url= http://dotw-xfer01.dot.state.nc.us/imgdot/DOTStateTravelMapHistoric/STM1980.pdf |format= PDF |title= North Carolina Official Highway Map |cartography= NCDOT |year= 1979 |accessdate= June 10, 2014}}</ref>  In 2010, NC&nbsp;138's northern terminus was truncated further south along a new routing of US&nbsp;52.<ref>{{cite web |publisher= North Carolina Department of Transportation |url= https://connect.ncdot.gov/resources/safety/Route%20Changes/2010_10_19.pdf |format= PDF |title=Route Change (2010-10-19) |date= October 19, 2010 |accessdate= June 10, 2014}}</ref>

